The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	New Delhi: Former Pakistan captain Wasim Akram feels Virat Kohli can become the future captain of India if he continues to work hard.    
	Virats performances in ODIs have been really good, but now the time has come for graduation. If he works hard on all aspects of his game, he can be a future captain for India. He seems to have all the makings of a leader, Akram said.         
	Adelaide: England batsman Kevin Pietersen has branded groundsmen at the Adelaide Oval pathetic after a practice session before the second Ashes Test against Australia was forced indoors because of rain. Pietersen launched his outburst on his Twitter account after showers prevented England from taking a nets session outside on Wednesday.        
	Islamabad: The Pakistan Cricket Boards decision to appoint former Test captain Javed Miandad as batting and fielding consultant with the national team has run into trouble as Miandad is not willing to accept the terms and conditions of his contract as batting consultant, like working under Waqar Younis.         
	Bhubaneswar: Former Australian one-day specialist, Michael Bevan, has been approached by the Orissa Cricket Association (OCA) to join it as an advisor for the development of the sport. Bevan was here for three days and visited the state-run academy.         
	Calcutta: Afghanistan coach Rashid Latif reckons the self-belief in his side will be the key to extending their winning run in the ICC Intercontinental Cup, as they prepare for the final against Scotland, which begins Thursday, in Dubai.         
	Chennai: A total of 24 Formula 1600 CC cars would be in action on the grid in the MRF Formula Championship 2011 to be run as a support race for the inaugural Formula One Indian Grand Prix slated for October 29-30 at the Jaypee International Race Circuit in Greater Noida.          
	New Delhi: Former AIFF general secretary Alberto Colaco winning the AFC Distinguished Service Award has kicked up a controversy with top officials accusing him of recommending himself without consulting the executive committee.         
	New Delhi: Pankaj Advani, has turned down offers from Bollywood filmmakers, citing time contraints because of his crazy schedule.        
	St Petersburg: US Open champion Kim Clijsters has been named the WTAs player of the year for the second time. Clijsters won five tournaments, including the season-ending WTA Championships and her second consecutive title at Flushing Meadows.     
